        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The goal of the program is to obtain continuum image of the Denebola cold planetesimal belt at 1.3 mm (230 GHz). Given its young age, one might expect to detect gas in the disk; therefore, we will search for CO (2-1) line in one of the lower sidebands with a spectral resolution of 1.3 km/s. The expected line width is 5-7 km/s estimated from the Keperian velocity at 30-50 AU around an 1.5 solar mass star. Therefore, the adopted spectral resolution is sufficiently enough to detect the CO (2-1) line at no extra cost in continuum sensitivity. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The observation is designed to use the C36-2 configuration, yielding an average resolution of 0.8" with the maximum recoverable size of 11". The cold planetesimal belt is expected to have an inner radius of 2.7" from the star. The beam size of 0.8", a physical resolution of 8.8 AU at the distance of the object, is sufficiently enough to put constraints on the width of the cold belt, and also resolve the detailed structure near the inner boundary from the star (and from the inner ice-line belt). The expected maximum size of the large mm grains is 10" in diameter, within the maximum recoverable size of the C36-2 configuration. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We use SED models fitted to the detailed shape of the disk SED, composed of measurements from Spitzer and Herschel, to estimate the expected flux density at 1.3 mm and disk surface brightness. For the expected disk surface brightness, we assume an axis-symmetric geometry (no density enhancement/clump) and geometric information (inclination of 55 degrees from face-on and position angle of 125 degrees) revealed from the marginally resolved 70 micron image. Hence, it represents a worst-case view of the ALMA detection limits. If the ring is clumpy (resonance structures with unseen planets), the disk will be more strongly detected. 

The model disk surface brightness has a peak value of 58 uJy/beam with a beam size of 0.8" at 1.3 mm. At the location of Denebola, a ~5-hour on-source intergration time can reach a rms of 7.3 uJy/beam, as given by the ALMA sensitivity calculator at 230 GHz in the continuum setup (bandwidth of 7.5 GHz at dual polarization) with the 12-m array. We, therefore, expect the cold planetesimal belt to be detected at 8 sigma levels. At the young age of Denebola, one might expect to detect gas in the disk; therefore, we will also search for CO (2-1) line with 1.3 km/s resolution in one of the lower sidebands. The Keplerian velocity of the cold planetesimal belt is in the range of 5-7 km/s; therefore, the planned spectral resolution (1.3 km/s) is sufficiently enough to search for CO line with a width of 5-7 km/s at no extra cost in continuum sensitivity. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
