    <prp:abstract>Denebola (beta Leo) is only slightly more distant than Fomalhaut, of virtually identical spectral type and luminosity, and has a nearly equally prominent debris disk. However, its disk is 2-4 times smaller than Fomalhaut's. The Denebola disk has at least four spectral/spatial components, presumably reflecting the complexity of the planetary system embedded in it. We propose to use ALMA to determine the structure of this disk, probing the embedded planetary system and allowing a detailed comparison with Fomalhaut's disk to elucidate the causes for the differences in their structures.</prp:abstract>
